# Open PR Flow

Invoke with: *"open pr flow"*, *"open pr"*, *"create pr"*, *"pr flow"*

---

## Workflow Steps

When the user triggers this workflow, execute these steps automatically in order:

### 1. Ask for PR details
- Ask the user for:
  - **Branch name** (suggest one based on recent changes)
  - **Commit message** (suggest one based on modified files)
  - **PR title** (default to commit message)
  - Confirm before proceeding

### 2. Create branch and commit
```bash
# Create and switch to new branch
git checkout -b <branch-name>

# Stage all modified/new files
git add -A

# Commit with the message
git commit -m "<commit-message>"
```

### 3. Build and verify
Run all build and type checks **before pushing**. If any step fails, stop and fix before proceeding.

```bash
# Build shared first (other packages depend on it)
npm run build -w packages/shared

# Type check server
npm run typecheck -w packages/server

# Build server
npm run build -w packages/server

# Build client (includes tsc + vite build)
npm run build -w packages/client

# Run tests
npm run test
```

If **any build or typecheck fails**:
- Stop the flow
- Show the error to the user
- Fix the issue
- Re-run the failing step
- Only proceed when all pass

### 4. Rebase on main
```bash
# Fetch latest main
git checkout main
git pull origin main

# Switch back and rebase
git checkout <branch-name>
git rebase main
```

If rebase has conflicts, stop and ask the user to resolve.

### 5. Push the branch
```bash
# Push (force after rebase)
git push -u origin <branch-name> --force-with-lease
```

### 6. Open PR
```bash
gh pr create --title "<pr-title>" --body "$(cat <<'EOF'
## Summary
<auto-generated from commit message and changed files>

## Changes
<list packages/files modified>

## Test plan
- [ ] Server starts without errors
- [ ] Client builds and loads
- [ ] Key features verified locally
EOF
)"
```

### 7. Output
- Print the PR URL in the terminal
- Confirm the branch is up to date and all checks passed

---

## Important Notes

- NEVER force push to `main` or `master`
- ALWAYS build and typecheck before pushing -- do not push broken code
- ALWAYS rebase on latest main before opening PR
- If rebase has conflicts, stop and ask the user to resolve
- Use conventional commit format: `feat:`, `fix:`, `refactor:`, `chore:`
- The PR body should summarize what changed based on the actual diff
- After PR is created, stay on the feature branch (don't switch back to main)
- If build fails after rebase (due to conflicts with main), fix and amend the commit
